{
  "answer": "**There is no passage in *Andreas* (cynewulf-andreas-07b573) that names a specific number of days spent at sea.** \n\nThe poem describes Andrew's sea voyage to Mermedonia in real time—boarding the ship, a storm, conversations, sleep, and sudden arrival at dawn—with no mention of elapsed days or nights on the water.[^1] Other numbered time periods appear (e.g., Matthew's 30-day wait for execution,[^2] 20 nights remaining on that sentence,[^3] three days/nights of Andrew's later torments on land,[^4] seven nights' stay in the city[^5]), but none quantify the sea journey itself. The voyage is divinely swift, aided by God and angels disguised as sailors.",
